  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       APPENDIX A — MEDICATION REVIEW
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card appendix-card" id="appendix-meds">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>

    <h3>💊 Morphine Sulfate 1 mg/mL — IV/SQ</h3>
    <table class="data-table med-table">
      <tbody>
        <tr><th>Classification</th><td>Opioid analgesic (Schedule II controlled substance)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Indication (Samuel)</th><td>Pain control and dyspnea relief in terminal pulmonary cancer</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Mechanism</th><td>Binds mu-opioid receptors in the CNS; alters pain perception and reduces respiratory distress sensation</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Principle of Double Effect</th><td>Adequate doses to control pain are <em>ethically justified</em> even if they may secondarily hasten death — the intent is comfort, not euthanasia</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Adverse effects</th><td>Respiratory depression · Sedation · Constipation · Nausea · Hypotension · Pruritus</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Contraindications</th><td>Hypersensitivity to opioids; severe respiratory depression (note: in hospice, respiratory depression may be an acceptable secondary effect of comfort dosing)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Nursing precautions</th><td>Assess behavioral pain cues and respiratory status before each dose · Have naloxone available per facility policy · In hospice, the goal is comfort — document response · Do not withhold adequate analgesia out of fear of respiratory depression</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Reversal agent</th><td>Naloxone (Narcan) — available; use is uncommon in hospice and must align with DNR/goals of care</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">💊 Metoclopramide</h3>
    <table class="data-table med-table">
      <tbody>
        <tr><th>Classification</th><td>Antiemetic / Dopamine antagonist / Prokinetic agent</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Indication (Samuel)</th><td>Nausea and vomiting management; gastroparesis secondary to cancer or opioid use</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Mechanism</th><td>Blocks dopamine D2 receptors in the chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) and enhances GI motility</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Adverse effects</th><td>Extrapyramidal symptoms (restlessness, involuntary movements, tardive dyskinesia with long-term use) · Drowsiness · Diarrhea · Akathisia</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Contraindications</th><td>Bowel obstruction or perforation · History of tardive dyskinesia · Pheochromocytoma</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Nursing precautions</th><td>Monitor for extrapyramidal effects — especially restlessness or involuntary facial movements · Avoid in bowel obstruction · Assess for nausea before administration and document response</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">💊 Glycopyrrolate</h3>
    <table class="data-table med-table">
      <tbody>
        <tr><th>Classification</th><td>Anticholinergic agent</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Indication (Samuel)</th><td>Reduce excessive oral and respiratory secretions causing "death rattle"</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Mechanism</th><td>Blocks muscarinic acetylcholine receptors → reduces production of oral, bronchial, and pharyngeal secretions</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Key distinction</th><td>Does NOT cross the blood–brain barrier → no sedation; does NOT dry up <em>existing</em> secretions — repositioning helps mobilize pooled secretions</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Why it matters for the family</th><td>The death rattle is distressing to families; glycopyrrolate reduces new secretion production and lessens the sound, reducing family distress</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Adverse effects</th><td>Dry mouth · Urinary retention · Constipation · Tachycardia · Blurred vision · Anhidrosis (reduced sweating)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Nursing precautions</th><td>Educate family that the gurgling sound does not indicate pain · Reposition patient to lateral position to help drain secretions · Monitor for urinary retention · Document family response to the intervention</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       APPENDIX B — HOSPICE PRINCIPLES
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card appendix-card" id="appendix-hospice">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Hospice Principles — Key Concepts</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>What Hospice Provides</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Pain and symptom management (comfort-focused)</li>
          <li>Spiritual care and chaplaincy services</li>
          <li>Emotional support for patient <em>and</em> family</li>
          <li>Caregiver support and respite care</li>
          <li>Social work services</li>
          <li>Bereavement support after death (typically 13 months)</li>
          <li>24-hour availability of care coordination</li>
        </ul>
        <h3 style="margin-top: 1rem;">What Hospice Does NOT Provide</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Curative or aggressive life-prolonging treatments</li>
          <li>Resuscitation (per DNR — aligned with patient's goals)</li>
          <li>Diagnostic testing aimed at cure</li>
          <li>Chemotherapy or radiation (unless for symptom palliation)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>The Interdisciplinary Hospice Team</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>RN / Hospice Nurse</th><td>Coordinates care, manages symptoms, supports family</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Physician / Medical Director</th><td>Certifies terminal diagnosis; manages medication orders</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Social Worker</th><td>Psychosocial support, financial resources, family dynamics</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Chaplain / Spiritual Care</th><td>Spiritual assessment, prayer, connecting to clergy</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Bereavement Counselor</th><td>Pre- and post-death grief support for family</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Home Health Aide</th><td>Personal care, hygiene, ADL assistance</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Volunteers</th><td>Companionship, respite, practical support for families</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout callout-info" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          <strong>Medicare Hospice Benefit:</strong>
          <p>Patients are eligible when two physicians certify a prognosis of ≤ 6 months if the disease runs its normal course. Patients must elect hospice and agree to forgo curative treatment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       APPENDIX C — KÜBLER-ROSS STAGES OF GRIEF
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card appendix-card" id="appendix-grief">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix C</span>
      <h2>Kübler-Ross Stages of Grief</h2>
    </div>

    <p>Dr. Elisabeth Kübler-Ross identified five stages of grief in her 1969 work <em>On Death and Dying</em>. Remember with the mnemonic <strong>DABDA</strong>.</p>

    <table class="data-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Stage</th>
          <th>What the Person May Say or Do</th>
          <th>Nursing Response</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>1. Denial</strong></td>
          <td><em>"This can't be happening."</em> Refusal to accept the diagnosis; seeking second opinions; minimizing the severity</td>
          <td>Be present; do not argue or force acceptance; provide honest, gentle information</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>2. Anger</strong></td>
          <td><em>"Why me? Why us? This isn't fair."</em> Directing anger at God, providers, family, or the healthcare system</td>
          <td>Allow and validate the anger; do not take it personally; maintain therapeutic presence; avoid defensiveness</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>3. Bargaining</strong></td>
          <td><em>"If I can just make it to my granddaughter's wedding…"</em> Attempting to negotiate more time with God, providers, or fate</td>
          <td>Listen empathetically; support the patient's goals for meaningful time; involve chaplaincy if desired</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>4. Depression</strong></td>
          <td>Withdrawal, crying, silence, mourning the upcoming loss and what will be left behind</td>
          <td>Provide a quiet, supportive presence; do not force conversation; offer social work and chaplain support</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>5. Acceptance</strong></td>
          <td><em>"I'm ready."</em> Coming to terms with the reality of death; focusing on saying goodbye and completing unfinished business</td>
          <td>Support the patient's and family's peaceful process; facilitate final wishes; honor spiritual practices</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <strong>⚠️ Critical Nursing Point:</strong>
      <p>People do <strong>not</strong> move through these stages in a set linear order. They may move back and forth between stages, skip stages, or experience several simultaneously. <strong>A nurse must meet the patient and family where they are</strong> — not where you think they should be. Never rush or judge a person's grieving process.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       APPENDIX D — POST-SIM QUESTIONS & ANSWERS
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card appendix-card" id="appendix-postsim">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix D</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: Upon entering the room, the nurse hears Mrs. Green praying. What should the nurse do?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>B. Wait quietly outside the room until they are done praying.</strong></p>
        <p>Prayer is a sacred act and should never be interrupted by routine nursing care. Standing quietly outside until prayer is finished demonstrates respect for the family's spiritual practices without abandoning the patient. Walking up to the bedside during prayer without an invitation would be intrusive and disrespectful.</p>
        <p>Once prayer has concluded, approach gently: <em>"I didn't want to interrupt. I'm here whenever you are ready."</em></p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What are Kübler-Ross's five stages of grief? (See Appendix C for full details)</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Denial</strong> — "This can't be happening."</li>
          <li><strong>Anger</strong> — "Why me? Why us?"</li>
          <li><strong>Bargaining</strong> — "If I can just make it to my granddaughter's wedding…"</li>
          <li><strong>Depression</strong> — Withdrawal, crying, mourning the upcoming loss</li>
          <li><strong>Acceptance</strong> — "I'm ready." Coming to terms with death</li>
        </ol>
        <p>People do not move through these stages in order. Nurses must meet each person where they are in the grieving process.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: You are caring for a terminally ill patient from a different culture. Discuss culturally competent care.</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Culturally competent end-of-life care requires the nurse to:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ask, don't assume:</strong> <em>"What is most important to you right now?"</em> and <em>"What are your beliefs about death and dying?"</em></li>
          <li>Recognize that grief expressions vary — weeping, silence, prayer, and ritual behaviors are all valid</li>
          <li>Understand that faith may alter responses to illness, treatment, DNR, organ donation, and postmortem care</li>
          <li>Use certified medical interpreters for language barriers — <em>never</em> use family as medical interpreters</li>
          <li>Practice active listening, therapeutic silence, and culturally appropriate touch</li>
          <li>Proactively consult chaplaincy and culturally competent resources</li>
          <li>Ask: <em>"Who provides the most support for you?"</em> and <em>"Which rituals or practices are important to you?"</em></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: After completing postmortem care, what does the nurse document?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>Time and date of death and all nursing actions taken</li>
          <li>Name of the provider certifying the death and time of notification</li>
          <li>All persons notified — family, provider, charge nurse, chaplain, social worker, coroner if applicable</li>
          <li>Condition of the body at time of death</li>
          <li>Postmortem care performed and who performed it</li>
          <li>Cultural or religious accommodations provided</li>
          <li>Disposition of the body — transferred to funeral home or morgue</li>
          <li>Personal belongings and valuables — documented and transferred to family with signature</li>
          <li>Bereavement resources offered</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: What is the most appropriate plan of care goal when addressing grief?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>The most appropriate goal statement is <strong>patient/family-focused, realistic, and measurable</strong>. Good examples:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><em>"Family will verbalize understanding of what to expect during the dying process by end of shift."</em></li>
          <li><em>"Patient will demonstrate signs of comfort (relaxed facial expression, absence of moaning) within 30 minutes of analgesic administration."</em></li>
          <li><em>"Family will identify at least one available support resource (chaplain, social worker) before the end of shift."</em></li>
        </ul>
        <p>Goal statements must include a <strong>subject, action verb, criteria, and time frame</strong>. Avoid vague goals like "patient will be comfortable" without measurable indicators.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

